          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Because s-reduction is a gradient feature, analysts often use acoustic measures to determine the extent of reduction and to classify tokens allophonically. This typically involves a combined Center of Gravity (COG) and Standard Deviation (SD) Measurement in Hertz (Hz). The COG measurement tells us the average frequency of the sound, whereas the SD tells us the dispersion of sound relative to that average. That is, a high COG (~6-10kHz) and a low SD indicate a very high frequency flow of concentrated air moving through a relatively small airway, which is characteristic [s], whereas lower COG and higher SD indicate less-concentrated air moving through a larger opening as occurs with [h]. Below are spectrograms showcasing [s] and [h], as well as two forms of deletion: one where the etymological place of /s/ is trace-marked with a pause, and another where the segment is elided entirely. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
