    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The alternation between these forms is not random, but conditioned by a combination of language-internal and -external factors, including phonological environment, interactional setting, role alignment, and encoded stance and affect. In Puerto Rico, [s] is recognized as having a historic connection to notions of formality, education, and institutional authority, while aspiration [h] and deletion [∅] are linked to informal settings and everyday speech. However, these associations are not stable or uniform. Aspirated [h], for example, is often positively evaluated as an authentic marker of Puerto Rican identity, particularly in casual contexts. Deletion [∅], by contrast, is more heavily stigmatized. While evaluations depend on the stance and background of the hearer and their perceptions of the speaker's background, there is research suggesting that full deletion is contrasted against [s] as indexing a lack of education or a lower socioeconomic status. There is also research to suggest that [s] carries gendered and sexuality-based associations, being heard as a \"feminine\" feature characteristic of the speech of women and gay men. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "https://drive.google.com/file/d/1AzZxTlX98SzLxXRQPwKlhQANKeLMB2hP/view?usp=sharing",
      "caption": "An Indexical Field of /s/ reduction in Puerto Rico",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "s-Reduction illustrates how regional phonological features become reinterpreted as markers of social alignments. In musical performance, these variants are not inherited from the spoken registers of the performers, but strategically deployed as part of the stylization of the musical product. s-Reduction in reggaetón, in particular, plays a central role in constructing the voice of the genre, and is adopted by both speakers from within and without Puerto Rico. \n"
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "center",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-two",
          "text": "/s/ in Reggaetón "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "S-Reduction carries high salience in reggaetón production and is even visible in online lyric transcriptions through the use of apostrophes (e.g., \""
        },
        {
          "text": "no me mire' así",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "\"). This feature is by far the most thoroughly researched phonological variable in the Hispanic Linguistics literature, which could explain why most research on reggaetón singing styles has used it as the locus of analysis. The following examples showcase how findings from contemporary research frame lenited /s/ as an enregistered resource for constructing and performing artistic alignment with the broader reggaetón soundscape. Throughout these examples, AVAnnotate's annotation feature provides transcriptions of the lyrics to highlight cases of reduction. For accessibility, this variability is presented binarily as \"retention [s] or reduction [h ʔ ø]\" marked in brackets as [s] or [-]. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "as curated from research comparing reggaetón's vocal style to other genres and the speech of Puerto Rican and non-Puerto Rican performers. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Throughout reggaetón's history, globalization, and various artistic developments, s-reduction has remained an audible aspect of the tracks. Below are examples ranging from 1996 to 2022 showcasing the Underground, Luny Tunes, Latin-Pop, and Contemporary eras of reggaetón production. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
